<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,925,1094]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,925,950]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robertson" authorityYear="1903" box="[282,435,926,949]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Diceratosmia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[282,435,926,949]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diceratosmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName box="[847,920,926,949]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[847,920,926,949]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Osmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in North America by the combination of the coarse punctures of the body; narrow apical fasciae of pale tomentum present on at least the basal metasomal terga; somewhat elongate parapsidal lines; carinate hind coxae; doubly carinate posterior margin of S4 of the males; and strong lateral teeth on T6 of the males. Members of this subgenus also share the somewhat unusual character of having pale scopal hairs (white, golden, or reddish golden).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
